{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592938"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:20:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:20:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15289"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15289"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7980"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69017"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7980"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15289"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54474"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7633"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19414"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19416"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69017"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHepatocyte injury can lead to characteristic histological findings that help identify the underlying pathology. On microscopic examination, certain intracytoplasmic inclusions may be visible within damaged liver cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the eosinophilic inclusions composed of damaged intermediate filaments in hepatocytes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mallory-Denk bodies","Councilman bodies","Russell bodies","Hyaline bodies","Lafora bodies"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMallory-Denk bodies\u003C/strong\u003E are eosinophilic intracytoplasmic inclusions found within injured hepatocytes. They are composed of damaged intermediate filaments (particularly keratins 8 and 18), ubiquitin, and heat shock proteins. These inclusions are most commonly associated with alcoholic liver disease but can also be seen in non-alcoholic steatohepatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECouncilman bodies\u003C/strong\u003E are acidophilic structures representing apoptotic hepatocytes, typically seen in viral hepatitis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERussell bodies\u003C/strong\u003E are distended rough endoplasmic reticulum containing immunoglobulins found in plasma cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyaline bodies\u003C/strong\u003E are intracytoplasmic inclusions characteristic of hepatocellular carcinoma\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELafora bodies\u003C/strong\u003E are periodic acid-Schiff positive inclusion bodies found in neurones and other tissues in Lafora disease, a form of progressive myoclonic epilepsy\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mallory-Denk bodies are damaged intermediate filaments (keratins 8 and 18) that accumulate in injured hepatocytes.","Mallory-Denk bodies are commonly found in alcoholic liver disease and non-alcoholic steatohepatitis.","Mallory-Denk bodies contain ubiquitin and heat shock proteins in addition to damaged intermediate filaments."],"references":["Torbenson M, Washington K. Pathology of liver disease: advances in the last 50 years. Hum Pathol. 2020 Jan;95:78-98. doi: 10.1016/j.humpath.2019.08.023. Epub 2019 Sep 4. PMID: 31493428","Chan WK, Chuah KH, Rajaram RB, Lim LL, Ratnasingam J, Vethakkan SR. Metabolic Dysfunction-Associated Steatotic Liver Disease (MASLD): A State-of-the-Art Review. J Obes Metab Syndr. 2023 Sep 30;32(3):197-213. doi: 10.7570/jomes23052. Epub 2023 Sep 13. PMID: 37700494; PMCID: PMC10583766","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54474"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15289"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54474"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T20:31:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T20:33:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7980"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69017"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com